[2]
Date: 26 Mar 2014
Source: Public Health Agency of Canada [edited]
http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/tmp-pmv/notices-avis/notices-avis-eng.php?id=125


The Ministry of Health of Guinea is currently reporting a rapidly evolving outbreak of Ebola haemorrhagic fever.

The WHO does not recommend that any travel or trade restrictions be applied to Guinea in relation to this outbreak.

The risk is low for most travellers, although the risk may increase for those who are working in a health care setting. The Public Health Agency of Canada recommends travellers in Guinea avoid direct contact with blood or bodily fluids of a person or corpse infected with the Ebola virus. Also, avoid contact with or handling an animal suspected of having Ebola haemorrhagic fever.

[See much more detail on precautions at the source.]

