[3]
Date: [undated]
Source: International Association for Medical Assistance to Travellers (IAMAT) [edited]
http://www.iamat.org/disease_details.cfm?id=145


Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever (EHF), also known as Ebola virus disease (EVD), is a highly contagious infection caused by one of 5 virus species belonging to the Filoviridae family believed to be carried by fruit bats. Serological evidence suggests the presence of Ebola virus in Cameroon, the Central African Republic, Chad, Ethiopia, Guinea, Kenya, Liberia, Madagascar, Nigeria, and Sierra Leone.

Prevention: Travellers going to affected areas should refrain from visiting households or healthcare settings that have been affected by an Ebola outbreak. Those who care for patients with suspected or confirmed Ebola cases should wear protective gowns, gloves, masks, as well as a face shield. Avoid eating meat from primates and monkeys as well as contact with dead animals. Practice good personal hygiene, and wash your hands frequently and thoroughly.

There is currently no commercially available vaccine or preventive medication against Ebola hemorrhagic fever.

