*******
[4]
Date: 24 Mar 2014
Source: UK National Travel Health Network & Centre (NaTHNaC) [edited]
http://www.nathnac.org/travel/news/ebola_guinea_240314.htm


On 23 Mar 2014, the World Health Organization (WHO) was notified of confirmed cases of Ebola haemorrhagic fever by the Ministry of Health in Guinea. The diagnosis of Ebola was laboratory confirmed.

Advice for travellers:
Guinea is not a common destination for UK travellers (with around 2600 visits by UK residents a year on average, mostly business travellers) [3]. The risk to most travellers is very low. There have been no known imported cases of Ebola in the United Kingdom to date [4].

Transmission of Ebola can only occur when there is direct contact with the blood or body fluids of an infected person, animal, or objects, such as needles, that have been contaminated with blood or body fluids. Travellers should avoid all contact with animals and with infected patients.

